snippet.textDisplay: That's not quite how cameras work I'm afraid :/. Shutter speed is one of the points on the ISO, Shutter speed and Apature triangle. A photo that takes longer to take or takes multipul let's say 1 second photos brings in more light compaired to a photo that's taken relt fast or multipul photos taken at 0.5 seconds. The only other way of increasing light is via a higher ISO (that will increase noise (the little spots you may see on photos taken in dark places) or a larger Apature (which decreases sharpness but improves bokah (background blur). There is one other way, that's with a larger sensor that's why DSLR's will always have an edge over phones. Increasing the processor won't improve on this,  not unless it has super software that can also compleatly get rid of ISO noise (iso btw is digital brightening). think of it this way, If you attach a high megapixel Webcam to a beast of a computer with the latest desktop processor and graphics, you still won't be able to get the kind of images that rely compaire to that of a DSLR, and that's even with the more processing power you can get out of a desktop over the likes of a phone or a DSLR. its more about light and physics then about how powerful a device is for photos :)

snippet.textDisplay: I have a 3-year old iPhone which is still at 100% health. I have always charged up with the ‘slow’ charger that came with phone. I keep the battery between 55-80% after visiting batteryuniversity.com and reading an article about extending the life of your battery. LION batteries hate heat so using ‘fast chargers’ really shorten the lifespan of battery. If changing phone every year it doesn’t matter how much you decrease lifespan as next owner will have to replace the battery sooner. I intend to keep the phone another 2 years hopefully so it’s imperative that I extend the lifespan of the battery as long as possible.
